🧠 Core Intuition (VERY IMPORTANT)
🔑 Key Observation:

You can swap indices i and j only if (j - i) is even

👉 That means:

Even index ↔ Even index ✅
Odd index ↔ Odd index ✅
Even ↔ Odd ❌ (IMPOSSIBLE)
💡 So what does this mean?

You are NOT free to rearrange entire string

Instead, you have 2 independent groups:

Group	Indices
Even positions	0, 2, 4, ...
Odd positions	1, 3, 5, ...

👉 You can freely permute within each group.

🎯 Final Condition:

For both strings to be equal:

Characters at even indices must match in frequency
Characters at odd indices must match in frequency
❌ Problem in Your Code

Your logic is correct, but:

Using map → slower (log n)
Doing erase operations → unnecessary overhead

We can optimize using arrays (O(1))

🚀 Optimized Approach (BEST)

Instead of map, use 2 arrays:

even[26]
odd[26]
⚡ Optimized Code
class Solution {
public:
    bool checkStrings(string s1, string s2) {
        vector<int> even(26, 0), odd(26, 0);

        for (int i = 0; i < s1.size(); i++) {
            if (i % 2 == 0)
                even[s1[i] - 'a']++;
            else
                odd[s1[i] - 'a']++;
        }

        for (int i = 0; i < s2.size(); i++) {
            if (i % 2 == 0)
                even[s2[i] - 'a']--;
            else
                odd[s2[i] - 'a']--;
        }

        // check all zero
        for (int i = 0; i < 26; i++) {
            if (even[i] != 0 || odd[i] != 0)
                return false;
        }

        return true;
    }
};
⚡ Why This is Better?
Approach	Time	Space
Your (map)	O(n log n)	O(n)
Optimized (array)	O(n)	O(1)

